</span></code></div></div></pre><ul><li>Used in low-level threading (e.g., <strong>kernel locks</strong>) when waiting times are very short.</li></ul><hr><h2><strong>4. Summary</strong></h2><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th><strong>Signal (Blocking)</strong></th><th><strong>Busy Waiting (Polling)</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>CPU Usage</strong></td><td>CPU <strong>sleeps</strong> until an event happens</td><td>CPU <strong>loops continuously</strong>, wasting resources</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Efficiency</strong></td><td><strong>Highly efficient</strong>, only runs when needed</td><td><strong>Inefficient</strong>, wastes CPU</td></tr><tr><td><strong>OS Involvement</strong></td><td><strong>Yes</strong>, the OS puts the thread in a wait queue</td><td><strong>No</strong>, the CPU keeps checking the condition</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Used In</strong></td><td><strong>Thread synchronization, I/O waiting</strong></td><td><strong>Spinlocks, very short waits</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p>üöÄ <strong>Signals are almost always better</strong> unless you need ultra-low-latency waits (like in high-frequency trading).</p><p>Would you like a deeper dive into how OS wakeup mechanisms work?</p></div>